The Telegraph - Calcutta
US take 2-1 lead
- Netherlands win rain-delayed doubles
 Bob and Mike Bryan of the US celebrate their win in Delray Beach on Saturday. (AFP) New York: Brothers Mike and Bob Bryan beat Jonas Bjorkman and Thomas Johansson 6-3, 6-4, 6-4 in the doubles rubber on Saturday to give the United States a 2-1 lead over Sweden in their Davis Cup quarter final clash. Despite losing their service at the start of the first two sets, the animated American pair  the worlds No. 1 doubles team  were far too strong for Bjorkman and Johansson in Delray Beach, Florida. An early lead in the third set for the Americans was pegged back by Bjorkman and Johansson, but there was little chance of an upset. In Mallorca, the Netherlands fought back from two sets down to win the rain-delayed doubles in their quarter final against Spain on Sunday and now trail the home side 1-2 in the tie. Losing two sets to one when the match was halted due to a downpour on Saturday, the Dutch pair of Martin Verkerk and John van Lottum staged an impressive recovery to claim a gritty 3-6, 2-6, 6-3, 6-2, 6-2 win over Spains Tommy Robredo and Rafael Nadal. In Lausanne, Roger Federer defeated Arnaud Clement 6-2, 7-5, 6-4 to help Switzerland level 2-2 in another quarter final tie on Sunday. Nicolas Escude and Michael Llodra defeated Federer and Yves Allegro in the doubles on Saturday to give France a 2-1 lead. In Minsk, Belarus completed their 5-0 whitewash of Argentina winning the reverse singles. On Sunday, Max Mirnyi beat Lucas Arnold 6-1, 6-2 while Vladimir Voltchkov overcame Juan Monaco 3-6, 6-3, 6-3. Spain went 2-0 up in the tie on Friday after Carlos Moya and Juan Carlos Ferrero both claimed easy victories over respective opponents Verkerk and Raemon Sluiter. Pumped up by a noisy Dutch contingent of fans, Verkerk and van Lottum tore into the inexperienced Spanish pair. (Reuters)  Copyright 
